Can you provide a C# code for implementing a binary search tree with a balanced structure to optimize search efficiency? It should include a `Balance` function to balance the tree, a `RotateLeft` and `RotateRight` function to perform tree rotation, and a `Height` function to calculate the height of a node. The code should also incorporate the use of generics to allow for different data types to be stored in the tree. Please provide a sample implementation.

### Response:
Certainly! Here's an example implementation of a balanced binary search tree in C#:
```csharp
public class BalancedBST where T : IComparable
{
 private class Node
 {
 public T Value;
 public Node Left;
 public Node Right;
 public int Height;
 public Node(T value)
 {
 Value = value;
 Height = 1;
 }
 }
 private Node root;
 public void Insert(T value)
 {
 root = Insert(root, value);
 }
 private Node Insert(Node node, T value)
 {
 if (node == null)
 return new Node(value);
 if (value.CompareTo(node.Value) < 0)
 node.Left = Insert(node.Left, value);
 else
 node.Right = Insert(node.Right, value);
 node.Height = 1 + Math.Max(Height(node.Left), Height(node.Right));
 int balance = GetBalance(node);
 if (balance > 1 && value.CompareTo(node.Left.Value) < 0)
 return RotateRight(node);
 if (balance < -1 && value.CompareTo(node.Right.Value) > 0)
 return RotateLeft(node);
 if (balance > 1 && value.CompareTo(node.Left.Value) > 0)
 {
 node.Left = RotateLeft(node.Left);
 return RotateRight(node);
 }
 if (balance < -1 && value.CompareTo(node.Right.Value) < 0)
 {
 node.Right = RotateRight(node.Right);
 return RotateLeft(node);
 }
 return node;
 }
 public void Balance()
 {
 List nodes = InOrderTraversal();
 root = BuildTree(nodes, 0, nodes.Count - 1);
 }
 private Node BuildTree(List nodes, int start, int end)
 {
 if (start > end)
 return null;
 int mid = (start + end) / 2;
 Node node = new Node(nodes[mid]);
 node.Left = BuildTree(nodes, start, mid - 1);
 node.Right = BuildTree(nodes, mid + 1, end);
 node.Height = 1 + Math.Max(Height(node.Left), Height(node.Right));
 return node;
 }
 private int Height(Node node)
 {
 if (node == null)
 return 0;
 return node.Height;
 }
 private int GetBalance(Node node)
 {
 if (node == null)
 return 0;
 return Height(node.Left) - Height(node.Right);
 }
 private Node RotateRight(Node node)
 {
 Node left = node.Left;
 Node right = left.Right;
 left.Right = node;
 node.Left = right;
 node.Height = 1 + Math.Max(Height(node.Left), Height(node.Right));
 left.Height = 1 + Math.Max(Height(left.Left), Height(left.Right));
 return left;
 }
 private Node RotateLeft(Node node)
 {
 Node right = node.Right;
 Node left = right.Left;
 right.Left = node;
 node.Right = left;
 node.Height = 1 + Math.Max(Height(node.Left), Height(node.Right));
 right.Height = 1 + Math.Max(Height(right.Left), Height(right.Right));
 return right;
 }
 public bool Search(T value)
 {
 Node node = root;
 while (node != null)
 {
 if (node.Value.Equals(value))
 return true;
 if (value.CompareTo(node.Value) < 0)
 node = node.Left;
 else
 node = node.Right;
 }
 return false;
 }
 public List InOrderTraversal()
 {
 List nodes = new List();
 InOrderTraversal(root, nodes);
 return nodes;
 }
 private void InOrderTraversal(Node node, List nodes)
 {
 if (node != null)
 {
 InOrderTraversal(node.Left, nodes);
 nodes.Add(node.Value);
 InOrderTraversal(node.Right, nodes);
 }
 }
}
```
In this implementation, the `BalancedBST` class is a generic class that can store any type of value that implements the `IComparable` interface. The `Node` class is a private nested class that represents a node in the tree. Each node has a value, a left child, a right child, and a height. The `root` field is a reference to the root node of the tree.
The `Insert` method inserts a new value into the tree. It first recursively inserts the value into the appropriate subtree. Then, it updates the height of the current node and checks whether the tree is balanced. If the tree is unbalanced, it performs one or two rotations to balance the tree.
The `Balance` method balances the tree by performing an in-order traversal of the tree to get a sorted list of nodes. It then recursively builds a new balanced tree from the sorted list.
The `RotateLeft` and `RotateRight` methods perform left and right rotations, respectively, on a given node.
The `Search` method searches for a value in the tree by traversing the tree from the root node until it finds the value or reaches a null node.
The `InOrderTraversal` method performs an in-order traversal of the tree and returns a list of nodes in sorted order.
Here's an example usage of the `BalancedBST` class:
```csharp
