### Response:
Sure, here's an example of C++ code that reads the "sentence" and "transformations" fields from a JSON string and applies the transformations to the original sentence:
```c++
#include 
#include 
#include 
#include "json.hpp"
using json = nlohmann::json;
int main() {
 // Example JSON string
 std::string jsonStr = R"({
 "sentence": "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.",
 "transformations": [
 {"operation": "reverse", "start": 4, "end": 9},
 {"operation": "capitalize", "start": 16, "end": 20},
 {"operation": "replace", "start": 28, "end": 31, "value": "cat"}
 ]
 })";
 // Parse the JSON string
 json jsonData = json::parse(jsonStr);
 // Extract the sentence and transformations fields
 std::string sentence = jsonData["sentence"];
 std::vector transformations = jsonData["transformations"];
 // Apply the transformations to the sentence
 for (const auto& transformation : transformations) {
 std::string operation = transformation["operation"];
 int start = transformation["start"];
 int end = transformation["end"];
 if (operation == "reverse") {
 std::reverse(sentence.begin() + start, sentence.begin() + end);
 } else if (operation == "capitalize") {
 for (int i = start; i < end; i++) {
 sentence[i] = toupper(sentence[i]);
 }
 } else if (operation == "replace") {
 std::string value = transformation["value"];
 sentence.replace(start, end - start, value);
 }
 }
 // Print the transformed sentence
 std::cout << sentence << std::endl;
 return 0;
}
```
In this example, we use the `nlohmann::json` library to parse the JSON string into a JSON object. We then extract the "sentence" and "transformations" fields from the JSON object and iterate through each transformation. Depending on the operation specified in each transformation object, we apply the corresponding transformation to the sentence. Finally, we print the transformed sentence. 
Note that this example assumes that the "start" and "end" fields in each transformation object are valid indices for the sentence string, and that "start" is less than "end". It also assumes that the "operation" field in each transformation object is one of "reverse", "capitalize", or "replace".

